{"id":"2110.13818","submitter":"Brian Freno","authors":"Brian A. Freno, Brian R. Carnes, Victor E. Brunini, Neil R. Matula","title":"Nonintrusive Manufactured Solutions for Non-Decomposing Ablation in Two\n  Dimensions","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Journal of Computational Physics (2022)","doi":"10.1016/j.jcp.2022.111237","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.comp-ph physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Code verification is a necessary step towards establishing credibility in\ncomputational physics simulations. It is used to assess the correctness of the\nimplementation of the numerical methods within the code, and it is a continuous\npart of code development. Code verification is typically performed using exact\nand manufactured solutions. However, exact solutions are often limited, and\nmanufactured solutions generally require the invasive introduction of an\nartificial forcing term within the source code, such that the code solves a\nmodified problem for which the solution is known. The equations for some\nphysics phenomena, such as non-decomposing ablation, yield infinite analytic\nsolutions, but the boundary conditions may eliminate these possibilities. For\nsuch phenomena, however, we can manufacture the terms that comprise the\nboundary conditions to obtain exact solutions. In this paper, we present a\nnonintrusive method for manufacturing solutions for non-decomposing ablation in\ntwo dimensions, which does not require the addition of a source term.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 26 Oct 2021 16:14:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 19 Mar 2022 16:27:15 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 26 Apr 2022 16:45:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-27"}
